The LHC is the largest and most powerful particle accelerator in the world. It is consists of a 27-Kilometer ring of superconducting magnets with some accelerating structures to boost the energy of the particles. Two high energy beams travel in a speed that is close to the speed of light before they collide. The beams travel in opposite directions along seperate pipes that are kept at ultrahigh vacuum. Particle beams are guided along a circular ring by strong magnetic field produced by superconducting electromagnets. The electromagnets are build from coils of electric cable that operates in superconducting state. LHC accelerate partices by "kicking" them with electric field. The electric field oscillate between positive and negative direction in certain frequency to produce electromangetic waves that accelerate particles in a "bunch" rather than in a stream. The reason is obvious, if the particles move in a bunch, the chances that particles collide each other is much higher. Once the particles are accelerated to certain speed, they are made to collide in four specific locations where the detectors are. The four locations correspond to: ATLAS,ALICE,CMS, and LHCb.
LHC has been used in particel physics research. It helps scientists to study particles in a sub-atomic level. When particles collide in a very high speed, the energy produced can simulate the beginning of the universe and produce particles such as Higgs boson for a fraction of a second before it decays to ordinary particles that are captured by the detectors. By a process of computational works, scientists can deduced the properties of the new particles that were created by the collsion.

The implication of those may not be obvious to us. However, when we look closely to the definition of those variable, we can get a sense of what they mean. First of all, let's look at the definition of 2 point and 3 point ECF. They are basically the sum of the particle to total momentum ratio multiplying by the relative distance of the pairs of 2 and 3 particles over all the jets. The ECF itself may not suggests anything. However, the ratio of 3 to 2 point ECF ratio yields some information of the particle production. By looking at the value of , we can tell if the particle production is a 1-prong or 2-prong production. (1-prong means that there is 1 particle in the end of the decay and 2-prong means that there are 2 particles in the end of the decay). By looking at the contour plot of , we can identify the 1-prong region and 2-prong region because 1-prong productions yield a higher value while 2-prong production yield lower value. We have two sets of data, one named higgs the other named qcd.
To see the differences in these two data sets, it is a good idea to plot variables of the two data sets individually and compare them.
%plot pt of higgs and qcd data

hold on
histogram(qcd(1,:),50)

title('Distribution of p_{T}')
ylabel('Counts')
xlabel('p_{T}')
hold off
The distribution of qcd data looks like a Rayleigh distribution while the distribution of higgs data does not look like the common distribution. It looks like a mix of more than one distribution.
%plot eta of higgs and qcd data

hold on

ylabel('Counts')

hold off
The distribution of η in both qcd and higgs data look like a Gaussian distribution. The only difference is the Gaussian distribution in the higgs data is narrower. This may suggests that the angles of particle trajectories in the higgs data are smaller than the angles of particle trajectories in the qcd data. In another word, the transverse momentums of the particles in higgs data are lower than the transverse momentums of the particles in qcd data.
